The suggested workaround in https://youtrack.jetbrains.com/issue/PY-36444/PyCharm-doesnt-infer-types-when-using-contextlib.contextmanager-decorator is ugly as shit:

```python
def successful_workaround_using_wrapper_function_annotated_returning_context_manager():
    """PyCharm autocompletion works and mypy is also happy, however this is an ugly workaround"""

    def wrapper() -> ContextManager[str]:
        @contextmanager
        def generator_function():
            yield "some value"

        return generator_function()

    with wrapper() as value:
        print(value.upper())  # PyCharm autocompletion works
```

I think this one is much better, it allows both pycharm autocompletion as well as typechecking of the original function, doesn't incur any runtime penalt, and is relatively small and unobtrusive

